Shall I wasting in despair, like leaves undone by autumn’s breath,
Drifting where the cold winds bear whispers of a life half-lived, half-dead?
No—let sorrow carve its name on canyon walls where rivers rise;
Let my grief be seed, not flame, sprouting courage toward the skies.
I will not dissolve in night, nor let silence be my shroud;
For every tear that blinds my sight becomes a star when spoken loud.
Though shadows stretch and time may tear the fabric of my trembling soul,
I’ll gather up the fractured parts and make a mosaic whole.
Not in vain these aching years, not in silence shall they pass;
I’ll wear my scars like battle gear, forged in sorrow, tempered glass.
So no, I shall not waste away where hollow echoes dare to creep;
I’ll rise—a phoenix from the gray—and sing while mountains weep.
